WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.832
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.140 --> 00:00:09.777
DANIEL JACKSON: This project
is, in a sense, an MIT project

00:00:09.777 --> 00:00:10.610
through and through.

00:00:10.610 --> 00:00:12.320
It's about MIT.

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:13.790
It was produced at MIT.

00:00:13.790 --> 00:00:16.040
It was funded by MIT grants.

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:19.400
But in some sense, I think
there's nothing about MIT

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:20.130
here at all.

00:00:20.130 --> 00:00:25.015
This is a universal project
about a universal problem.

00:00:25.015 --> 00:00:27.390
But I have to start by telling
you a little bit about MIT

00:00:27.390 --> 00:00:29.630
and where this
project came from.

00:00:29.630 --> 00:00:33.432
So as many of you probably know,
MIT's a rather quirky place.

00:00:33.432 --> 00:00:35.390
It's probably one of the
only universities that

00:00:35.390 --> 00:00:37.660
has an annual piano
drop, and this

00:00:37.660 --> 00:00:40.660
is a picture I took of
the piano drop in 2015,

00:00:40.660 --> 00:00:43.580
and there is the
piano about to fall.

00:00:43.580 --> 00:00:48.200
And MIT is a quirky place, full
of fun things and fun people

00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:50.250
mostly having a good time.

00:00:50.250 --> 00:00:53.780
But it's also a
highly competitive,

00:00:53.780 --> 00:00:54.890
high-pressure environment.

00:00:54.890 --> 00:00:57.223
I'm sure none of you have
ever been in a place like that

00:00:57.223 --> 00:00:58.430
before.

00:00:58.430 --> 00:01:00.950
And that can exact its costs.

00:01:00.950 --> 00:01:07.177
And in 2014, 2015 we had a
terrible mental health crisis.

00:01:07.177 --> 00:01:09.260
That makes it sound as if
it came out of the blue.

00:01:09.260 --> 00:01:12.170
The truth is it had been
brewing for a long time,

00:01:12.170 --> 00:01:15.230
but it really came to
a head in that year.

00:01:15.230 --> 00:01:21.600
In 2014 in particular, four
students took their lives,

00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:25.430
and my colleague Seth
Teller died that summer too.

00:01:25.430 --> 00:01:28.160
At the same time, there
were smaller crises

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:31.370
happening everywhere-- just
the burden of depression

00:01:31.370 --> 00:01:35.349
and anxiety at MIT was
increasing year by year.

00:01:35.349 --> 00:01:36.890
And I had noticed
this in my courses.

00:01:36.890 --> 00:01:42.200
I would have, typically, when I
started teaching, maybe none--

00:01:42.200 --> 00:01:45.950
maybe a couple of students who
had some issue during the term.

00:01:45.950 --> 00:01:51.230
By 2014, 2015, I was often
having 5 or 10 or more students

00:01:51.230 --> 00:01:53.361
coming to me during the term.

00:01:53.361 --> 00:01:55.610
They would normally come and
say that they wanted help

00:01:55.610 --> 00:01:58.070
with a problem set, and then
once we sat down and talked,

00:01:58.070 --> 00:02:01.910
it became clear that they had
no difficulty understanding

00:02:01.910 --> 00:02:02.480
the material.

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:04.160
They had no lack of talent.

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:07.100
They were just suffering
from, basically,

00:02:07.100 --> 00:02:11.150
a major episode of
anxiety or depression

00:02:11.150 --> 00:02:14.950
that was preventing them
from doing their work.

00:02:14.950 --> 00:02:17.510
And this is actually a
shot of my office window

00:02:17.510 --> 00:02:19.220
in the lovely Stata Center.

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:22.610
And so this got me thinking
about how pervasive depression

00:02:22.610 --> 00:02:26.360
and anxiety at MIT had become
and how big a problem it was.

00:02:26.360 --> 00:02:31.520
And then in the spring of 2015,
when this photo was taken--

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:35.330
as you know, this is what spring
often looks like in Boston--

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:38.000
it was a really terrible time.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:43.722
In a week in March 2015, two
students took their own lives

00:02:43.722 --> 00:02:44.430
in the same week.

00:02:44.430 --> 00:02:48.020
And the shock of
these two deaths

00:02:48.020 --> 00:02:50.450
really galvanized
the entire community,

00:02:50.450 --> 00:02:53.870
and the MIT newspaper published
a series of articles--

00:02:53.870 --> 00:02:55.490
a remarkable
editorial-- about how

00:02:55.490 --> 00:02:58.440
it was time for us to
face up to this issue,

00:02:58.440 --> 00:03:00.740
but also two articles
in particular that

00:03:00.740 --> 00:03:02.300
really struck a chord with me.

00:03:02.300 --> 00:03:03.950
One was this article--

00:03:03.950 --> 00:03:07.700
a guest column by a sophomore
called Karen [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:07.700 --> 00:03:10.700
about her own
experience with dealing

00:03:10.700 --> 00:03:12.270
with her own depression.

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:15.220
The other was an article
by Professor John Belcher,

00:03:15.220 --> 00:03:16.670
that it was actually
republished--

00:03:16.670 --> 00:03:19.850
it had actually been
published previously in 2012,

00:03:19.850 --> 00:03:22.430
and that article had been
inspired by an article,

00:03:22.430 --> 00:03:27.380
I think, in 2010 by a student
whose name was Grace Taylor.

00:03:27.380 --> 00:03:30.590
And one of the things that I
noticed about these articles

00:03:30.590 --> 00:03:34.130
was that they produced
an extraordinary wave

00:03:34.130 --> 00:03:35.930
of consolation--

00:03:35.930 --> 00:03:37.310
particularly in
the student body,

00:03:37.310 --> 00:03:39.840
but I think in the
institute as a whole.

00:03:39.840 --> 00:03:42.410
And there was something
just incredibly reassuring

00:03:42.410 --> 00:03:45.530
about people
standing up in public

00:03:45.530 --> 00:03:47.330
and saying this
is a real problem,

00:03:47.330 --> 00:03:49.215
and I've experienced
this problem

00:03:49.215 --> 00:03:50.840
and I've grappled
with it, and I'm here

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:54.020
to tell you that I came out
the other side of the tunnel.

00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:56.129
It's possible to do that.

00:03:56.129 --> 00:03:57.170
And this got me thinking.

00:03:57.170 --> 00:03:59.930
It got me thinking in particular
about how important it

00:03:59.930 --> 00:04:04.580
was that they had their
names on these articles.

00:04:04.580 --> 00:04:06.140
I suspect at Google,
too-- at MIT,

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:07.790
we have what you might call--

00:04:07.790 --> 00:04:11.300
what I like to call a
geek libertarian culture,

00:04:11.300 --> 00:04:13.520
and that culture often
puts what I think

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:17.450
is actually an inappropriate
value on anonymity.

00:04:17.450 --> 00:04:20.690
Because a lot of people are
very concerned about privacy,

00:04:20.690 --> 00:04:24.060
they think anonymity is
somehow a good thing in itself.

00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:27.530
And what I noticed was that when
people used anonymous forums

00:04:27.530 --> 00:04:30.590
to talk about things that
they weren't happy about,

00:04:30.590 --> 00:04:32.510
it didn't have this
consoling effect.

00:04:32.510 --> 00:04:35.090
And I came to actually
think that perhaps it had

00:04:35.090 --> 00:04:36.770
exactly the opposite effect--

00:04:36.770 --> 00:04:38.660
that there's actually
something that

00:04:38.660 --> 00:04:43.700
reinforces stigma about
expressing yourself

00:04:43.700 --> 00:04:45.060
anonymously.

00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:48.410
Anyway, so like many
other people at MIT,

00:04:48.410 --> 00:04:49.820
I was wondering
if anything could

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:52.430
be done to respond to
these horrible tragedies

00:04:52.430 --> 00:04:57.050
and to do something
to help our culture.

00:04:57.050 --> 00:04:59.870
Anyway, so as [INAUDIBLE]
mentioned, I'm a photographer.

00:04:59.870 --> 00:05:03.170
And every summer, I'd
been going off to Maine--

00:05:03.170 --> 00:05:05.460
to the Maine Media
Workshops up in Camden,

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:07.800
which is this fantastic
place that has--

00:05:07.800 --> 00:05:12.000
I don't know-- 30, 40,
50 photography workshops

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:13.110
every summer.

00:05:13.110 --> 00:05:14.910
They last a week long,
and you study them

00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:18.690
with one photographer and
it's a remarkable experience.

00:05:18.690 --> 00:05:20.390
And I'd been going
for many years,

00:05:20.390 --> 00:05:22.530
and that summer I studied
with a photographer

00:05:22.530 --> 00:05:25.266
called Joyce Tenneson.

00:05:25.266 --> 00:05:27.390
And one of the great things
about these experiences

00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:30.660
is that you learn not only
a lot about their style

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:33.120
of photography and
their aesthetics

00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:35.612
and the way they go about
constructing an image,

00:05:35.612 --> 00:05:38.070
but you also get to learn about
their life and the way they

00:05:38.070 --> 00:05:39.910
think about their career.

00:05:39.910 --> 00:05:43.050
And Joyce said something
that was really remarkable

00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:47.370
and that really
struck me very deeply.

00:05:47.370 --> 00:05:49.720
This is a picture I took
of Joyce that summer.

00:05:49.720 --> 00:05:52.170
These are pictures that
Joyce is famous for.

00:05:52.170 --> 00:05:54.240
She'd been a commercial
photographer,

00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:59.250
and then she had really moved to
becoming a very successful art

00:05:59.250 --> 00:06:01.080
portrait photographer.

00:06:01.080 --> 00:06:03.400
She produced a book
called "Light Warriors"

00:06:03.400 --> 00:06:06.150
that these photographs
were taken from.

00:06:06.150 --> 00:06:10.860
And as she put it, she came to
realize that she was spending--

00:06:10.860 --> 00:06:13.470
or had spent--
much of her career

00:06:13.470 --> 00:06:17.310
making photos of beautiful,
young women in their 20s.

00:06:17.310 --> 00:06:19.860
And it suddenly
occurred to her that she

00:06:19.860 --> 00:06:22.290
was a woman in her 70s--

00:06:22.290 --> 00:06:24.090
early 70s, I guess.

00:06:24.090 --> 00:06:26.070
All her friends were
in their early 70s.

00:06:26.070 --> 00:06:30.840
And yet she was still taking
pictures of women in their 20s.

00:06:30.840 --> 00:06:33.450
And it occurred to her that
maybe what she should do

00:06:33.450 --> 00:06:37.232
is take pictures of beautiful
women in their 70s instead.

00:06:37.232 --> 00:06:38.940
And so what she did
was she did a project

00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:40.898
that she called "Wise
Women" where she traveled

00:06:40.898 --> 00:06:43.080
across the country,
and she took pictures

00:06:43.080 --> 00:06:46.230
of women between the
age of about 50 and 100.

00:06:46.230 --> 00:06:50.290
And she produced that book,
and it was a huge success.

00:06:50.290 --> 00:06:53.100
In fact, by her telling,
it was the biggest success

00:06:53.100 --> 00:06:54.330
of all her books.

00:06:54.330 --> 00:06:56.730
This anecdote really
got me thinking,

00:06:56.730 --> 00:07:01.080
and I started wondering
who are my wise women?

00:07:01.080 --> 00:07:03.870
As a photographer, if I
was going to come home,

00:07:03.870 --> 00:07:07.110
as it were, and find the people
who were my obvious subject

00:07:07.110 --> 00:07:09.840
rather than going to the
traditional art subjects,

00:07:09.840 --> 00:07:11.440
what might that subject be?

00:07:11.440 --> 00:07:13.050
And I realized--
well, that subject

00:07:13.050 --> 00:07:15.450
would have to be
people at MIT who

00:07:15.450 --> 00:07:20.260
were in the midst of this battle
against depression and anxiety.

00:07:20.260 --> 00:07:23.079
So I came back from this
workshop totally fired up

00:07:23.079 --> 00:07:25.620
with this idea that I was going
to do a project where I would

00:07:25.620 --> 00:07:28.800
make a gallery of photos of
people who had experienced

00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:29.910
depression and anxiety.

00:07:29.910 --> 00:07:33.069
And my idea was that by
showing this gallery,

00:07:33.069 --> 00:07:34.860
it would signal to
people that this was not

00:07:34.860 --> 00:07:35.984
something to be ashamed of.

00:07:35.984 --> 00:07:37.530
On the contrary,
this was something

00:07:37.530 --> 00:07:40.680
to be proud of-- to have
faced this enormous challenge

00:07:40.680 --> 00:07:46.500
and to have endured it, and
become even enriched by it.

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:49.290
And I hope that
in so doing, this

00:07:49.290 --> 00:07:51.810
would bring some consolation
and encouragement to people

00:07:51.810 --> 00:07:54.300
who are suffering
from these conditions,

00:07:54.300 --> 00:07:57.600
and it would also destigmatize
it for everybody else to see.

00:07:57.600 --> 00:08:00.020
And I also had this
feeling that these people

00:08:00.020 --> 00:08:01.980
had something to teach
us all, because one

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:05.259
of the ironies of the way
that we'd been thinking

00:08:05.259 --> 00:08:07.050
about mental health is
that a lot of people

00:08:07.050 --> 00:08:10.140
were talking about mental
health, a lot of the experts--

00:08:10.140 --> 00:08:12.150
the psychiatrists,
the psychologists,

00:08:12.150 --> 00:08:15.470
the anthropologists and so
on, and the administrators--

00:08:15.470 --> 00:08:17.820
but the people who actually
experienced depression

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:19.500
and anxiety, they
didn't seem to be

00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:21.990
playing a part in this
conversation at the institute

00:08:21.990 --> 00:08:22.770
level.

00:08:22.770 --> 00:08:24.300
So I wrote to the
three people who

00:08:24.300 --> 00:08:25.770
had published those articles--

00:08:25.770 --> 00:08:29.730
Karen the sophomore, John
Belcher the faculty member,

00:08:29.730 --> 00:08:32.039
and Grace, who had written
the original article.

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:34.049
She'd moved on to
Harvard Med School.

00:08:34.049 --> 00:08:36.600
And I asked the three of
them if they'd be Guinea pigs

00:08:36.600 --> 00:08:38.309
and if they'd let me
take photos of them

00:08:38.309 --> 00:08:42.480
as the beginning of a
gallery of photos of people.

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:46.740
And to my delight, they
accepted very enthusiastically.

00:08:46.740 --> 00:08:49.640
So I started by making
a photo of Karen,

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:53.160
and my original idea was to
make environmental pictures--

00:08:53.160 --> 00:08:55.650
whatever part of MIT they chose.

00:08:55.650 --> 00:08:57.861
And that turned out to
be a pretty crazy idea.

00:08:57.861 --> 00:08:59.610
This was taken in the
library, and it just

00:08:59.610 --> 00:09:02.730
wasn't the right kind of
private, quiet atmosphere

00:09:02.730 --> 00:09:03.690
to do that.

00:09:03.690 --> 00:09:07.500
So I switched to doing more
traditional studio-like shots.

00:09:07.500 --> 00:09:11.520
So this was the photo that
I ended up making of Karen,

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:13.830
and I took photos of
the three of them.

00:09:13.830 --> 00:09:15.600
And then at the end of--

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:17.040
that was 2015.

00:09:17.040 --> 00:09:18.900
At the end of the
year, with the help

00:09:18.900 --> 00:09:21.630
of some extraordinary
undergraduates,

00:09:21.630 --> 00:09:25.170
we pitched to "The Tech--" which
is the MIT school newspaper--

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:27.990
the idea of doing
a series in which,

00:09:27.990 --> 00:09:31.590
every week, we would put
up a picture of somebody

00:09:31.590 --> 00:09:35.400
and an excerpt about their life.

00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:37.710
And I should say originally
I was going to just

00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:40.510
have a little caption
associated with the picture,

00:09:40.510 --> 00:09:44.310
but as soon as I heard Karen's
story and the remarkable things

00:09:44.310 --> 00:09:46.562
she had to say, I
realized that there

00:09:46.562 --> 00:09:49.020
was an opportunity, essentially,
for a whole mini biography

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:49.560
here.

00:09:49.560 --> 00:09:51.210
So that's what the
project became.

00:09:51.210 --> 00:09:53.760
It became, basically,
a portrait in words,

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:57.100
and a portrait in an image.

00:09:57.100 --> 00:10:01.420
And at the beginning,
I was excited about it,

00:10:01.420 --> 00:10:03.610
but I have to
admit-- having agreed

00:10:03.610 --> 00:10:06.700
to produce one every
week of the term,

00:10:06.700 --> 00:10:09.850
you can imagine I thought-- wow,
that was a pretty crazy thing

00:10:09.850 --> 00:10:10.630
to do.

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:12.760
What the heck was I thinking?

00:10:12.760 --> 00:10:15.100
They'll never come.

00:10:15.100 --> 00:10:17.000
But they did come.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.830
And in fact, enough came not
only to publish one every week,

00:10:20.830 --> 00:10:24.040
but to get a few that I didn't
even have room for in the term,

00:10:24.040 --> 00:10:27.040
and that's eventually what led
to this book that you've seen.

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:28.780
So typically this is
what would happen.

00:10:28.780 --> 00:10:30.560
I would take a photo.

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:34.090
This is the wonderful
Victor Morales, whose story

00:10:34.090 --> 00:10:35.950
is completely remarkable.

00:10:35.950 --> 00:10:40.980
And then the MIT newspaper
published the photo.

00:10:40.980 --> 00:10:43.780
They usually gave us a full
page, which was wonderful,

00:10:43.780 --> 00:10:45.520
with the story around it.

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:48.700
The story is an entirely
verbatim accounting

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:49.990
by the subject.

00:10:49.990 --> 00:10:52.070
It was only minimally
edited by me.

00:10:52.070 --> 00:10:55.315
I basically recorded the story--

00:10:55.315 --> 00:10:59.050
I recorded their words, had
them transcribed, and then

00:10:59.050 --> 00:11:01.900
just minimally edited it,
removing "ums" and "ahs"

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:03.940
and punctuating it,
and occasionally moving

00:11:03.940 --> 00:11:06.940
things around to preserve
the chronological order

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:08.260
of the story.

00:11:08.260 --> 00:11:12.700
But aside from that, every
word in these stories

00:11:12.700 --> 00:11:14.720
was spoken to me.

00:11:14.720 --> 00:11:16.750
And then what I did
was I put up posters

00:11:16.750 --> 00:11:19.990
all around campus that said
if you have a story to tell,

00:11:19.990 --> 00:11:21.530
please come and tell it to me.

00:11:21.530 --> 00:11:23.740
And lots of them came.

00:11:23.740 --> 00:11:25.990
And by the end of
that first term,

00:11:25.990 --> 00:11:31.510
I'd interviewed 18 people,
which included mostly students--

00:11:31.510 --> 00:11:34.690
interestingly, mostly
women-- a couple

00:11:34.690 --> 00:11:39.280
of professors, and a bunch
of administrative staff.

00:11:39.280 --> 00:11:42.150
So that was what
happened that term,

00:11:42.150 --> 00:11:45.010
and then I decided that I--

00:11:45.010 --> 00:11:47.800
actually, to be honest, I
had hoped from the outset

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:49.494
that this would become
a book, because I

00:11:49.494 --> 00:11:51.160
had a sense that this
was something that

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:54.040
could be valuable beyond MIT.

00:11:54.040 --> 00:11:58.390
And so I proposed this
book to The MIT Press,

00:11:58.390 --> 00:12:01.450
and they agreed to publish it.

00:12:01.450 --> 00:12:05.020
I was very lucky that
two MIT organizations

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:07.050
helped fund this project.

00:12:07.050 --> 00:12:10.930
As a photographer, I wanted
to have a lovely book printed

00:12:10.930 --> 00:12:13.850
on very nice paper with a
very nice binding and so on,

00:12:13.850 --> 00:12:15.860
and that's incredibly expensive.

00:12:15.860 --> 00:12:19.420
So the book probably should
have cost $60 or $70,

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:23.080
but the MIT Council for the
Arts gave me their biggest grant

00:12:23.080 --> 00:12:24.510
of that year.

00:12:24.510 --> 00:12:27.220
And then I got another grant
from the MIT MindHandHeart

00:12:27.220 --> 00:12:29.140
Innovation Fund,
and that allowed

00:12:29.140 --> 00:12:32.740
us to subsidize the printing so
much that the book is actually

00:12:32.740 --> 00:12:34.270
relatively cheap--

00:12:34.270 --> 00:12:37.520
I think very cheap by the
standards of this kind of book.

00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:40.360
So they're typically going
between about $20 and $30

00:12:40.360 --> 00:12:45.520
a copy depending on Amazon's
current algorithmic state.

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:48.850
And then a wonderful thing
happened the following--

00:12:48.850 --> 00:12:51.820
actually, this was
before the book came out.

00:12:51.820 --> 00:12:53.740
An alumnus approached
me and said

00:12:53.740 --> 00:12:56.350
that he was very
interested in giving

00:12:56.350 --> 00:12:59.080
the book to new students
at MIT, and he proposed

00:12:59.080 --> 00:13:00.460
running a Pi Day Challenge.

00:13:00.460 --> 00:13:03.070
That's our MIT annual
fundraising day.

00:13:03.070 --> 00:13:08.440
And we ran that
challenge collaboration

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:10.900
with MindHandHeart, which
is the mental health

00:13:10.900 --> 00:13:15.250
initiative on campus, and
amazingly raised about $15,000

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:15.756
that day.

00:13:15.756 --> 00:13:17.380
And that was enough
money to buy a copy

00:13:17.380 --> 00:13:20.030
of the book for every student.

00:13:20.030 --> 00:13:22.420
So we gave a copy of the book
to every incoming student

00:13:22.420 --> 00:13:24.780
the following year.

00:13:24.780 --> 00:13:29.440
And since then, it's been a
really fun and exciting project

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:32.380
of basically taking
these remarkable stories

00:13:32.380 --> 00:13:34.900
of these extraordinary
people on the road

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:40.240
and trying to
proselytize for the book.

00:13:40.240 --> 00:13:43.330
We've had some wonderful
media engagements.

00:13:43.330 --> 00:13:45.450
And what, for me, has been
particularly wonderful

00:13:45.450 --> 00:13:46.908
is that on every
occasion when I've

00:13:46.908 --> 00:13:48.920
been invited to go
somewhere, I've always said,

00:13:48.920 --> 00:13:51.700
well, want my subjects, not me.

00:13:51.700 --> 00:13:53.570
And so they've
always come with me.

00:13:53.570 --> 00:13:57.040
This is in the BUR studio
for "All Things Considered"

00:13:57.040 --> 00:13:59.920
with Lisa Mullins, and
that's Emily Tang and Victor

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:03.680
Morales, who are both
extraordinary people.

00:14:03.680 --> 00:14:06.430
And actually, BUR
then played it--

00:14:06.430 --> 00:14:08.951
"All Things Considered" was
just a local production,

00:14:08.951 --> 00:14:11.450
but then they actually played
it nationally on "Here &amp; Now."

00:14:11.450 --> 00:14:13.100
So that was really terrific.

00:14:13.100 --> 00:14:18.250
And then we had a really
extraordinarily exciting

00:14:18.250 --> 00:14:23.710
opportunity that "PBS NewsHour"
decided to come to MIT

00:14:23.710 --> 00:14:26.560
and talk to us about the
story, and they actually

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:29.596
played two long segments
two nights in a row.

00:14:29.596 --> 00:14:30.970
This is the
classroom I teach in,

00:14:30.970 --> 00:14:33.370
and here are three of the
students being interviewed

00:14:33.370 --> 00:14:36.410
by Jeff Brown, the
arts correspondent.

00:14:36.410 --> 00:14:40.090
We also had a very entertaining
interview with Jim Braude,

00:14:40.090 --> 00:14:43.280
who some of you might know
from "Greater Boston."

00:14:43.280 --> 00:14:47.380
He's also on an NPR
show with Margery Eagen,

00:14:47.380 --> 00:14:50.140
and he's a very funny guy.

00:14:50.140 --> 00:14:51.790
This is Haley on the left.

00:14:51.790 --> 00:14:54.490
They're cracking up
after she calls him sir,

00:14:54.490 --> 00:14:58.120
and he exploded in amusement,
claiming that nobody had ever

00:14:58.120 --> 00:14:59.695
called him sir before.

00:14:59.695 --> 00:15:02.660
And I'd like to show
you a little video

00:15:02.660 --> 00:15:06.200
in which the subjects
speak for themselves.

00:15:06.200 --> 00:15:10.610
It starts with audio
excerpts from the interviews.

00:15:13.190 --> 00:15:16.490
And as you'll see, people
really said some amazing things

00:15:16.490 --> 00:15:18.170
about their life experience.

00:15:18.170 --> 00:15:22.130
And then it includes some
photographs that I took during

00:15:22.130 --> 00:15:24.050
the sessions-- many of
them not in the book--

00:15:24.050 --> 00:15:26.660
along with excerpts--
verbatim excerpts--

00:15:26.660 --> 00:15:29.660
from what they told me
during the interviews.

00:15:38.474 --> 00:15:39.140
