00:15:39.140 --> 00:15:41.360
- I committed a week before.

00:15:41.360 --> 00:15:44.810
I said yes to MIT, and then
she has this heart attack

00:15:44.810 --> 00:15:46.190
in front of me.

00:15:46.190 --> 00:15:48.200
So I went through with my plans.

00:15:48.200 --> 00:15:49.910
This is what I'm
doing in the fall.

00:15:49.910 --> 00:15:50.810
I'm going to college.

00:15:50.810 --> 00:15:54.024
And people die all the time.

00:15:54.024 --> 00:15:55.940
Everyone has to deal
with their parents' death

00:15:55.940 --> 00:15:56.830
if they have parents.

00:15:56.830 --> 00:16:00.140
This is something
I can deal with.

00:16:00.140 --> 00:16:02.660
And I think that was a mistake.

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:05.750
- Especially because
when someone dies,

00:16:05.750 --> 00:16:09.340
you don't know, necessarily,
until they're dead.

00:16:09.340 --> 00:16:11.770
You just take for
granted everything

00:16:11.770 --> 00:16:15.420
that they had been holding up.

00:16:15.420 --> 00:16:18.124
- So over those
next two days, I was

00:16:18.124 --> 00:16:19.290
feeling absolutely terrible.

00:16:19.290 --> 00:16:20.430
I had [INAUDIBLE] to do.

00:16:20.430 --> 00:16:23.480
I was already
getting really down,

00:16:23.480 --> 00:16:26.695
and I really wanted
to commit suicide.

00:16:26.695 --> 00:16:29.070
And I just said this to the
guy I was doing therapy with.

00:16:29.070 --> 00:16:31.410
And he was like, hm, I'm
going to have to go talk

00:16:31.410 --> 00:16:33.236
to someone about this.

00:16:33.236 --> 00:16:35.610
And as soon as he said that,
as soon as he left the room,

00:16:35.610 --> 00:16:36.235
I'm like, fuck.

00:16:36.235 --> 00:16:38.530
I'm getting transported.

00:16:38.530 --> 00:16:41.224
And sure enough, I sent
a message to Danny.

00:16:41.224 --> 00:16:42.640
I'm like, Danny,
I think I'm going

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:43.765
to get sent to [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:43.765 --> 00:16:45.730
- He stood at the
foot of my bed.

00:16:45.730 --> 00:16:49.110
He had a clipboard,
a stethoscope.

00:16:49.110 --> 00:16:51.690
He had a main tank,
a white coat--

00:16:51.690 --> 00:16:55.080
all the accoutrements
of authority.

00:16:55.080 --> 00:17:04.540
And he said, Mr. Kaiser,
your operation was a success.

00:17:04.540 --> 00:17:06.910
But I'm sorry to tell you
that you'll never walk again.

00:17:09.950 --> 00:17:15.180
Now, when he said that to me,
what I said inside my head was,

00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:17.569
fuck you.

00:17:17.569 --> 00:17:21.170
What I said to him was,
I'm sorry to hear that.

00:17:21.170 --> 00:17:23.069
- The big goal was to walk.

00:17:23.069 --> 00:17:29.240
And I remember when I
first stood on my legs,

00:17:29.240 --> 00:17:33.330
my hamstrings hurt so bad.

00:17:33.330 --> 00:17:36.090
- I always knew there
was something wrong.

00:17:36.090 --> 00:17:39.630
There's a better way
to live than this.

00:17:39.630 --> 00:17:43.440
I just didn't know where
it was or who knew that.

00:17:43.440 --> 00:17:47.640
I just knew that I just
felt crappy all the time

00:17:47.640 --> 00:17:50.310
when I was a kid, when
I was a teenager, when

00:17:50.310 --> 00:17:53.005
I was a young adult.

00:17:53.005 --> 00:17:54.380
- And then I went
to my therapist

00:17:54.380 --> 00:17:57.160
and I said, is this how
normal people feel every day?

00:17:57.160 --> 00:17:57.910
And she said, yes.

00:18:00.920 --> 00:18:05.490
And I said, well, I had no idea.

00:18:05.490 --> 00:18:08.040
- My medication mellowed me out.

00:18:11.220 --> 00:18:17.190
And it was a good thing,
because I wasn't having

00:18:17.190 --> 00:18:20.980
the extremes of the depression.

00:18:20.980 --> 00:18:23.070
So it helped me survive.

00:18:23.070 --> 00:18:28.980
- The most useful thing
I learned from being away

00:18:28.980 --> 00:18:35.400
was that you can
always ask for help,

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:37.800
and there will always be
someone to help you here.

00:18:40.794 --> 00:18:44.287
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:29:01.550 --> 00:29:02.870
[END PLAYBACK]

00:29:02.870 --> 00:29:06.080
DANIEL JACKSON: So I wanted
to close by telling you

00:29:06.080 --> 00:29:08.390
a few things that I
thought I learned from what

00:29:08.390 --> 00:29:10.010
my subjects taught
me, and then talk

00:29:10.010 --> 00:29:11.801
about what I think some
of the implications

00:29:11.801 --> 00:29:13.740
are for a place like Google.

00:29:13.740 --> 00:29:16.040
So the first thing I
learned from talking

00:29:16.040 --> 00:29:20.030
to all these people is how much
unhappiness is in the world.

00:29:20.030 --> 00:29:23.990
And I was reminded of this
remarkable comment from

00:29:23.990 --> 00:29:26.400
the Hasidic master, Rabbi
Nachman of Bratslav--

00:29:26.400 --> 00:29:29.660
who's widely thought to
have been bipolar himself--

00:29:29.660 --> 00:29:34.070
who basically said that
the principle that we all

00:29:34.070 --> 00:29:36.410
have to deal with is to
struggle with all our strength

00:29:36.410 --> 00:29:37.070
to be happy.

00:29:37.070 --> 00:29:40.160
That happiness is
not a natural state,

00:29:40.160 --> 00:29:43.760
but it is human nature to be
drawn to darkness and sadness.

00:29:43.760 --> 00:29:45.692
And sadly, I think,
that's really true.

00:29:45.692 --> 00:29:47.900
And so happy people aren't
people who are just lucky.

00:29:47.900 --> 00:29:49.756
They're people who work at it.

00:29:49.756 --> 00:29:52.130
The second thing-- which you
won't be surprised to hear--

00:29:52.130 --> 00:29:53.810
is that competition
really hurts.

00:29:53.810 --> 00:29:57.710
Everyone told a story of coming
from a high school where they

00:29:57.710 --> 00:30:00.800
were the top of 1,000
students, and they come to MIT,

00:30:00.800 --> 00:30:02.840
and they're just the
same as everybody else.

00:30:02.840 --> 00:30:05.970
You hit MIT, and it's
not enough anymore.

00:30:05.970 --> 00:30:10.050
I learned that depression--
that major depression--

00:30:10.050 --> 00:30:11.840
depression is really
on a spectrum,

00:30:11.840 --> 00:30:17.117
and that major depression is
a terrible, terrible disease.

00:30:17.117 --> 00:30:19.700
I mean, I knew already that it
wasn't just like being a little

00:30:19.700 --> 00:30:22.640
bit unhappy, but the people who
suffer from major depressive

00:30:22.640 --> 00:30:25.550
episodes go through
something that many of them

00:30:25.550 --> 00:30:28.880
describe as much worse
than physical pain.

00:30:28.880 --> 00:30:31.040
And it's a terrible and
debilitating disease

00:30:31.040 --> 00:30:33.920
that robs you,
more than anything,

00:30:33.920 --> 00:30:36.570
of your resilience,
which makes it very hard.

00:30:36.570 --> 00:30:39.290
I learned that relationships--
for all these people,

00:30:39.290 --> 00:30:42.490
they all explained how their
relationships to other people

00:30:42.490 --> 00:30:45.470
were really at the
center of their recovery,

00:30:45.470 --> 00:30:47.930
and Lydia in particular
said this remarkable thing,

00:30:47.930 --> 00:30:50.210
which has stuck in
my mind ever since.

00:30:50.210 --> 00:30:52.820
She said you don't
realize what people

00:30:52.820 --> 00:30:55.670
are doing in your life,
what roles they're playing,

00:30:55.670 --> 00:30:56.922
sometimes, until they die.

00:30:56.922 --> 00:30:58.880
And you don't know what
you're holding together

00:30:58.880 --> 00:30:59.900
in other people's lives.

00:30:59.900 --> 00:31:02.720
You might not know that you're
the glue holding together

00:31:02.720 --> 00:31:05.420
so much, because you
take yourself for granted

00:31:05.420 --> 00:31:07.857
like we take other
people for granted.

00:31:07.857 --> 00:31:09.440
So anyway, there are
many other things

00:31:09.440 --> 00:31:10.550
that I learned from
the book, and I

00:31:10.550 --> 00:31:12.425
hope you'll get a chance
to read the stories.

00:31:12.425 --> 00:31:15.260
I think they all have
really remarkable insights

00:31:15.260 --> 00:31:17.390
into the nature of
life and diversity

00:31:17.390 --> 00:31:21.230
and ideas for how
to achieve happiness

00:31:21.230 --> 00:31:23.420
in the face of obstacles.

00:31:23.420 --> 00:31:26.940
I want to say a few things
about resilience at work.

00:31:26.940 --> 00:31:31.100
The first is that these
conditions, if we're just

00:31:31.100 --> 00:31:34.250
talking narrowly about
anxiety ans depression

00:31:34.250 --> 00:31:36.210
and bipolar-- these
are universal.

00:31:36.210 --> 00:31:38.750
And so this is just
applying the normal rate.

00:31:38.750 --> 00:31:41.810
So if I'm assuming an almost
90,000 people at Google,

00:31:41.810 --> 00:31:44.630
that means you have about
18,000 people at Google who

00:31:44.630 --> 00:31:48.890
have a severe anxiety disorder,
about 7,000 who've experienced

00:31:48.890 --> 00:31:51.650
major depression,
and about 3,000

00:31:51.650 --> 00:31:53.550
who have bipolar disorder.

00:31:53.550 --> 00:31:56.630
So this is basically everywhere.

00:31:56.630 --> 00:31:59.210
It's pretty clear what
causes depression.

00:31:59.210 --> 00:32:01.550
We don't know, in any
individual, what the cause is,

00:32:01.550 --> 00:32:04.010
but in pretty much
all my stories,

00:32:04.010 --> 00:32:06.440
there's some combination of
a genetic predisposition,

00:32:06.440 --> 00:32:09.620
traumatic experiences, and
then a stressful life--

00:32:09.620 --> 00:32:12.890
not enough sleep and exercise,
poor social connectivity,

00:32:12.890 --> 00:32:15.470
and ultimately a
loss of self-worth--

00:32:15.470 --> 00:32:19.280
which seems to be the trigger
that, for a lot of people,

00:32:19.280 --> 00:32:22.280
really takes them to
a quite ruinous state.

00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:25.460
So I've thought a little
bit about strategies

00:32:25.460 --> 00:32:26.090
for resilience.

00:32:26.090 --> 00:32:28.340
First of all, to
value the whole person

00:32:28.340 --> 00:32:31.280
and to be very careful
about judging people

00:32:31.280 --> 00:32:33.140
on one dimension--
the way they perform

00:32:33.140 --> 00:32:37.010
on the team, what their program
ability is, whether they're

00:32:37.010 --> 00:32:41.270
intelligent only in a logical
sense rather than their larger

00:32:41.270 --> 00:32:44.120
emotional intelligence.

00:32:44.120 --> 00:32:47.390
Secondly, we always
pay lip service

00:32:47.390 --> 00:32:50.210
to rewarding the team
players, but do we really

00:32:50.210 --> 00:32:52.400
reward the team players
who actually build up

00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:53.870
the other members of the team?

00:32:53.870 --> 00:32:55.490
Who aren't just
team players because

00:32:55.490 --> 00:32:57.230
of their outsize
contribution to the end

00:32:57.230 --> 00:32:59.330
result, which is
different from really

00:32:59.330 --> 00:33:01.350
building the team itself?

00:33:01.350 --> 00:33:04.460
And I think one that I've
come to realize more and more

00:33:04.460 --> 00:33:07.490
as really critical is
that an organization needs

00:33:07.490 --> 00:33:10.310
to encourage people to be
able to acknowledge and talk

00:33:10.310 --> 00:33:12.530
about their own vulnerabilities.

00:33:12.530 --> 00:33:15.150
A friend of mine,
who's been educating me

00:33:15.150 --> 00:33:17.810
in organizational
matters, shared with me

00:33:17.810 --> 00:33:19.040
this extraordinary paper.

00:33:19.040 --> 00:33:22.221
It's quite old, and I
think it's from 2014--

00:33:22.221 --> 00:33:24.470
by Robert Kegan and his
colleagues at Harvard Business

00:33:24.470 --> 00:33:25.640
School.

00:33:25.640 --> 00:33:28.820
And the contention
of this paper is

00:33:28.820 --> 00:33:33.620
that if an organization
actually encourages people

00:33:33.620 --> 00:33:35.480
to be open about
their vulnerabilities

00:33:35.480 --> 00:33:39.350
and their weaknesses
and their obstacles that

00:33:39.350 --> 00:33:42.260
sit in front of them,
then it will actually

00:33:42.260 --> 00:33:44.930
be able to dramatically
not only change

00:33:44.930 --> 00:33:47.670
the environment in
the organization,

00:33:47.670 --> 00:33:51.470
but also to give people
opportunities for growth

00:33:51.470 --> 00:33:53.760
and improvement in their
lives and their careers

00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:56.690
that they wouldn't have
had in an organization that

00:33:56.690 --> 00:33:59.150
tends to want to
smother any talk of all

00:33:59.150 --> 00:34:00.180
these vulnerabilities.

00:34:00.180 --> 00:34:02.250
And this, to be honest,
is the biggest flaw

00:34:02.250 --> 00:34:04.280
that I see in our
culture at MIT.

00:34:04.280 --> 00:34:07.310
We're always rah-rahing
and saying we're so great.

00:34:07.310 --> 00:34:08.130
We're so amazing.

00:34:08.130 --> 00:34:09.590
We have all these
cool inventions.

00:34:09.590 --> 00:34:12.199
We have all these
amazing people.

00:34:12.199 --> 00:34:14.780
And the truth is
that can actually,

00:34:14.780 --> 00:34:17.420
ironically and paradoxically,
be a very negative message

00:34:17.420 --> 00:34:19.880
to a lot of people, because
the first thing it says

00:34:19.880 --> 00:34:22.760
is if you're not on this list of
people who have been mentioned

00:34:22.760 --> 00:34:24.260
as the great,
fantastic people, then

00:34:24.260 --> 00:34:26.340
there must be something
wrong with you.

00:34:26.340 --> 00:34:28.040
But it's also
saying subliminally

00:34:28.040 --> 00:34:30.639
if you feel, in any respect,
that the environment isn't

00:34:30.639 --> 00:34:33.380
perfect and that
you're not perfect

00:34:33.380 --> 00:34:36.889
and that you can't see a
direct path to huge success,

00:34:36.889 --> 00:34:39.080
then there must be something
very wrong with you.

00:34:39.080 --> 00:34:41.330
And that doesn't empower
people to be their best,

00:34:41.330 --> 00:34:44.210
and that doesn't actually
create an organization in which,

00:34:44.210 --> 00:34:47.600
rather than feeling jealous
or disappointed and angry

00:34:47.600 --> 00:34:51.101
and bitter about not
being the best achievers--

00:34:51.101 --> 00:34:53.600
it doesn't create an atmosphere
in which people can actually

00:34:53.600 --> 00:34:57.260
work together to
achieve great things.

00:34:57.260 --> 00:34:59.900
On the subject of
team players, I'm

00:34:59.900 --> 00:35:02.420
reminded by this
wonderful comment

00:35:02.420 --> 00:35:04.190
that Jerry Weinberg made--

00:35:04.190 --> 00:35:06.740
famously-- in his old
book on "The Psychology

00:35:06.740 --> 00:35:08.130
of Computer Programming."

00:35:08.130 --> 00:35:11.240
And he was talking more in
the context of programming

00:35:11.240 --> 00:35:13.520
in its various
problems, but I think

00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:17.360
it applies very much in
the emotional sense of team

00:35:17.360 --> 00:35:18.021
players.

00:35:18.021 --> 00:35:19.020
And here's what he said.

00:35:19.020 --> 00:35:22.010
He said if a programmer is
indispensable, get rid of him

00:35:22.010 --> 00:35:23.836
as soon as possible.

00:35:23.836 --> 00:35:25.460
And I think the only
way I would update

00:35:25.460 --> 00:35:29.010
this is by saying get rid of
him or her as soon as possible.

00:35:29.010 --> 00:35:30.650
But in every other
respect, I think

00:35:30.650 --> 00:35:36.290
this is just as powerful and
relevant as it has ever been.

00:35:36.290 --> 00:35:38.870
Strategies for
personal resilience--

00:35:38.870 --> 00:35:41.600
I think people have obviously
written a lot about this.

00:35:41.600 --> 00:35:46.400
To me, there are three that
I found particularly helpful

00:35:46.400 --> 00:35:49.340
and that, reflecting on
what my subjects told me,

00:35:49.340 --> 00:35:51.210
I think were influential
in their lives.

00:35:51.210 --> 00:35:54.290
One was to know what
your purpose is.

00:35:54.290 --> 00:35:56.090
And in particular,
for your purpose not

00:35:56.090 --> 00:36:01.400
to be a particular GPA or
getting a particular fellowship

00:36:01.400 --> 00:36:04.040
or getting your internship
at Google in the summer

00:36:04.040 --> 00:36:08.210
or getting a certain promotion
or having a certain salary

00:36:08.210 --> 00:36:11.270
or being at a certain
rank in your organization.

00:36:11.270 --> 00:36:12.780
None of those are a purpose.

00:36:12.780 --> 00:36:14.400
Those are all means to an end.

00:36:14.400 --> 00:36:16.820
And if you can have a real
sense of what your purpose is

00:36:16.820 --> 00:36:21.410
in life, that's a much truer
way to resilience and happiness.

00:36:21.410 --> 00:36:22.970
The second thing
is that people who

00:36:22.970 --> 00:36:25.670
are open to other people
about their own fears

00:36:25.670 --> 00:36:28.130
and vulnerabilities
end up being,

00:36:28.130 --> 00:36:31.959
I think, much happier and much
more resilient themselves.

00:36:31.959 --> 00:36:33.500
Partly because they
share the burden,

00:36:33.500 --> 00:36:35.870
partly because other
people respond in kind,

00:36:35.870 --> 00:36:38.217
and they realize
that the world is

00:36:38.217 --> 00:36:39.800
both a more vulnerable
place, but also

00:36:39.800 --> 00:36:42.780
a kinder and more supportive
place than they imagined.

00:36:42.780 --> 00:36:45.680
And I think the other thing
is that one of the things

00:36:45.680 --> 00:36:46.720
that we all do--

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:48.803
well, I won't say we all
do it, but I've certainly

00:36:48.803 --> 00:36:49.970
done enough of it myself--

00:36:49.970 --> 00:36:53.540
is we all play certain parts
and we all try and pretend,

00:36:53.540 --> 00:36:56.630
to some extent, to be
people that we are not.

00:36:56.630 --> 00:37:00.530
And particularly if
you're the kind of person

00:37:00.530 --> 00:37:03.392
who works for Google or MIT, you
could get pretty good at that.

00:37:03.392 --> 00:37:04.850
And then if you're
intelligent, you

00:37:04.850 --> 00:37:06.470
can sometimes play that game.

00:37:06.470 --> 00:37:10.320
But ultimately it comes back to
bite you, because ultimately,

00:37:10.320 --> 00:37:13.520
if you don't project yourself
for who you really are,

00:37:13.520 --> 00:37:15.560
then there will come a
point at which you're

00:37:15.560 --> 00:37:18.680
doing things you don't want
to be doing and presenting

00:37:18.680 --> 00:37:22.490
yourself in a way that
doesn't feel right.

00:37:22.490 --> 00:37:24.920
So I thought I
would ask you-- what

00:37:24.920 --> 00:37:28.670
do you think the biggest
challenge is that you face

00:37:28.670 --> 00:37:31.280
in the tech industry at
Google, or societally,

00:37:31.280 --> 00:37:32.930
organizationally,
and personally,

00:37:32.930 --> 00:37:38.270
and what are the best strategies
and opportunities to address

00:37:38.270 --> 00:37:40.504
that?

00:37:40.504 --> 00:37:42.170
I'll just show my
last slide, which is--

00:37:42.170 --> 00:37:45.740
I have a little resilience
postcard that I send out

00:37:45.740 --> 00:37:47.480
about once a month,
and I'd be delighted

00:37:47.480 --> 00:37:49.730
if you'd like to
subscribe to that.

00:37:49.730 --> 00:37:53.280
And you can find out more
about the book there.

00:37:53.280 --> 00:37:55.040
But at point, I think
I will stop talking,

00:37:55.040 --> 00:37:56.625
and I'd love to hear from you.

00:37:56.625 --> 00:38:00.020
[APPLAUSE]

00:38:01.364 --> 00:38:03.280
AUDIENCE: Doesn't quite
address your question,

00:38:03.280 --> 00:38:05.560
but do you have plans to
continue this project,

00:38:05.560 --> 00:38:07.754
or are you done with
this form of [INAUDIBLE]

00:38:07.754 --> 00:38:09.670
DANIEL JACKSON: I'm
trying to figure out how--

00:38:09.670 --> 00:38:12.045
I don't think I'm going to
continue it exactly like this,

00:38:12.045 --> 00:38:15.250
but I'm looking at
working with some people

00:38:15.250 --> 00:38:18.970
on some exciting projects
of a similar nature.

00:38:18.970 --> 00:38:20.410
I did a little
project, actually--

00:38:20.410 --> 00:38:22.270
which now seems quite timely.

00:38:22.270 --> 00:38:24.790
When the travel ban came
out I did a little project

00:38:24.790 --> 00:38:28.540
of a much smaller project
of photos and stories

00:38:28.540 --> 00:38:33.010
of MIT immigrants and
