00:39:52.820 --> 00:39:55.390
AUDIENCE: You mentioned that
more of the portraits that you

00:39:55.390 --> 00:39:57.520
took were of women than of men.

00:39:57.520 --> 00:40:00.460
Do you have any idea
why that might be?

00:40:00.460 --> 00:40:02.830
DANIEL JACKSON:
Well, my guess is

00:40:02.830 --> 00:40:05.320
just that women are
more open and are more

00:40:05.320 --> 00:40:07.180
willing to share these things.

00:40:07.180 --> 00:40:09.820
One of the very interesting
things was that the beginning

00:40:09.820 --> 00:40:12.280
of the project, when I sat
down with John Belcher--

00:40:12.280 --> 00:40:13.840
the professor--

00:40:13.840 --> 00:40:15.890
who was one of my Guinea
pigs at the start,

00:40:15.890 --> 00:40:18.550
he said to me, for old
fogies like you and me,

00:40:18.550 --> 00:40:21.207
this is easy, because
we have nothing to lose.

00:40:21.207 --> 00:40:21.790
We're tenured.

00:40:21.790 --> 00:40:22.850
We can't be fired.

00:40:22.850 --> 00:40:24.850
He said, you'll have no
trouble getting faculty.

00:40:24.850 --> 00:40:30.670
But students, they've got
their careers ahead of them.

00:40:30.670 --> 00:40:33.040
The idea of social
media being covered

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:35.270
with their early
troubles in life--

00:40:35.270 --> 00:40:36.590
they're not going to want that.

00:40:36.590 --> 00:40:40.240
And the fascinating thing was
it was exactly the opposite.

00:40:40.240 --> 00:40:42.670
By and large, with the exception
of two or three people,

00:40:42.670 --> 00:40:45.170
no faculty members
wanted to talk to me.

00:40:45.170 --> 00:40:47.030
And I know for sure
there are many, many,

00:40:47.030 --> 00:40:50.890
many who have experienced
depression and anxiety.

00:40:50.890 --> 00:40:54.040
And students, completely
to the contrary,

00:40:54.040 --> 00:40:58.030
had a extraordinary
openness and candidness.

00:40:58.030 --> 00:40:59.140
In fact, Krista Tippett--

00:40:59.140 --> 00:41:00.181
I don't know if you know.

00:41:00.181 --> 00:41:03.340
She's the host of this
wonderful NPR show, "On Being."

00:41:03.340 --> 00:41:05.980
She once commented--
actually, in an interview

00:41:05.980 --> 00:41:08.950
with danah boyd talking about
the internet and social media

00:41:08.950 --> 00:41:12.250
behavior-- how she thinks it's
almost a new kind of ethic

00:41:12.250 --> 00:41:15.790
that the way young
people behave in sharing

00:41:15.790 --> 00:41:19.610
has an openness and generosity
that's really unprecedented.

00:41:19.610 --> 00:41:21.280
And I certainly
experienced that,

00:41:21.280 --> 00:41:25.000
and I experienced it
particularly from these women

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:25.790
more than men.

00:41:25.790 --> 00:41:27.599
I tried to, actually,
get more men.

00:41:27.599 --> 00:41:29.890
One of my colleagues-- a
female colleague-- said to me,

00:41:29.890 --> 00:41:30.580
it's all women.

00:41:30.580 --> 00:41:31.660
Can't you get some men?

00:41:31.660 --> 00:41:33.280
And I said, I'm trying.

00:41:33.280 --> 00:41:37.510
But yeah, so I don't
know what it is,

00:41:37.510 --> 00:41:40.990
but there's certainly a
gender difference there.

00:41:40.990 --> 00:41:43.115
AUDIENCE: Hi, I missed the
first half of your talk,

00:41:43.115 --> 00:41:45.073
so I'm so sorry if you've
already covered this.

00:41:45.073 --> 00:41:47.140
But how do you think that
we can teach resilience

00:41:47.140 --> 00:41:48.444
to university students?

00:41:48.444 --> 00:41:50.110
Do you have any
strategies for that that

00:41:50.110 --> 00:41:52.630
work in the classroom, or
that can work in our meetings?

00:41:52.630 --> 00:41:54.760
DANIEL JACKSON: Sure.

00:41:54.760 --> 00:41:58.900
I think the main way that
we can teach resilience

00:41:58.900 --> 00:42:03.040
is by example, is by the way
that we talk about the goals

00:42:03.040 --> 00:42:06.130
that we set for ourselves
and for each other,

00:42:06.130 --> 00:42:12.070
and by making a culture in
which we actually value openness

00:42:12.070 --> 00:42:15.640
and encourage people to
share their struggles,

00:42:15.640 --> 00:42:18.970
with the idea that that's
the way you become better.

00:42:18.970 --> 00:42:20.530
Just one thing that
occurred to me--

00:42:20.530 --> 00:42:22.720
I realized that for
a long time, I'd

00:42:22.720 --> 00:42:25.880
been saying we should value
people for who they are,

00:42:25.880 --> 00:42:28.240
not because they've
won certain prizes

00:42:28.240 --> 00:42:29.770
or have certain possessions.

00:42:29.770 --> 00:42:32.050
And then one day,
sitting in a lecture,

00:42:32.050 --> 00:42:35.110
seeing someone introduced,
the person said, and I'd

00:42:35.110 --> 00:42:37.330
like to introduce you to my
colleague so-and-so who's

00:42:37.330 --> 00:42:42.340
won A, B, C, and D prizes
and whose article is

00:42:42.340 --> 00:42:44.240
the most cited, blah,
blah, blah and so on.

00:42:44.240 --> 00:42:46.270
And I realized I've
done that myself,

00:42:46.270 --> 00:42:48.580
and that completely
undermines any claim

00:42:48.580 --> 00:42:51.880
that these proxy measures don't
matter when you're constantly

00:42:51.880 --> 00:42:54.220
sending a subliminal
message to the students

00:42:54.220 --> 00:42:56.830
that actually, these are
the things that count.

00:42:56.830 --> 00:42:58.570
And so I think we
need to change the way

00:42:58.570 --> 00:43:00.670
we talk about these
things and I think

00:43:00.670 --> 00:43:08.260
we need to try and value people
in a much more holistic way.

00:43:08.260 --> 00:43:11.380
I think that would produce
the biggest effect.

00:43:11.380 --> 00:43:12.970
I think we also
somehow simply need

00:43:12.970 --> 00:43:16.220
to crank down all the pressure.

00:43:16.220 --> 00:43:19.120
I'm not sure how to do that, but
we certainly need to do that--

00:43:19.120 --> 00:43:22.720
give people time to mull
things over a bit more.

00:43:22.720 --> 00:43:24.940
AUDIENCE: One of the
things is by the time

00:43:24.940 --> 00:43:31.330
they get to college, there's
already some processes in place

00:43:31.330 --> 00:43:34.960
and some experiences that
these kids have, and is there

00:43:34.960 --> 00:43:39.850
any things that you guys are
looking into around earlier

00:43:39.850 --> 00:43:43.900
experiences that can help
students coming in already

00:43:43.900 --> 00:43:46.614
prepared with resilience?

00:43:46.614 --> 00:43:48.530
DANIEL JACKSON: Whoa,
that's a great question.

00:43:48.530 --> 00:43:49.990
I don't know.

00:43:49.990 --> 00:43:52.870
Yeah, I'm not part of the team
that worries about this at MIT,

00:43:52.870 --> 00:43:54.370
but I think you're
absolutely right.

00:43:54.370 --> 00:43:57.670
It's often well-established.

00:43:57.670 --> 00:44:00.520
But in my experience talking
to the subjects of my book,

00:44:00.520 --> 00:44:02.560
it's often in early
childhood that they

00:44:02.560 --> 00:44:05.380
had traumatizing experiences,
and those experiences then

00:44:05.380 --> 00:44:06.700
come up much later.

00:44:06.700 --> 00:44:09.370
They get triggered by their
experience in university

00:44:09.370 --> 00:44:10.910
or in the workplace.

00:44:10.910 --> 00:44:14.240
And so I think you'd
have to go way back.

00:44:14.240 --> 00:44:15.280
So I suspect we also--

00:44:15.280 --> 00:44:16.250
I mean, I have a--

00:44:16.250 --> 00:44:18.520
and I'm sure you've read
the famous Jean Twenge

00:44:18.520 --> 00:44:20.770
article in "The Atlantic"
about mobile devices

00:44:20.770 --> 00:44:22.720
and those extraordinary
graphs that

00:44:22.720 --> 00:44:25.390
show the advent of the
iPhone almost perfectly

00:44:25.390 --> 00:44:30.100
correlated with huge
drops in social activity,

00:44:30.100 --> 00:44:32.530
whether it's driving
cars, going out

00:44:32.530 --> 00:44:35.230
with friends, sexual
intercourse-- everything

00:44:35.230 --> 00:44:38.650
plummets in 2009 with
the advent of the iPhone.

00:44:38.650 --> 00:44:41.410
And just anecdotally,
I think a lot of people

00:44:41.410 --> 00:44:45.340
are feeling that devices
are a very large part

00:44:45.340 --> 00:44:47.530
of the alienation that
young people feel,

00:44:47.530 --> 00:44:50.519
and that that's dramatically
exacerbating the problem.

00:44:50.519 --> 00:44:52.810
So maybe as a technologist,
one of the things we can do

00:44:52.810 --> 00:44:54.670
is work on that.

00:44:54.670 --> 00:44:57.070
AUDIENCE: So you would
ask what does Google

00:44:57.070 --> 00:44:58.180
do to help its employees?

00:44:58.180 --> 00:44:59.950
And I still remember
the orientation--

00:44:59.950 --> 00:45:01.900
that they point out
that you will feel

00:45:01.900 --> 00:45:03.970
overwhelmed in the beginning.

00:45:03.970 --> 00:45:04.820
This is expected.

00:45:04.820 --> 00:45:05.860
This is normal.

00:45:05.860 --> 00:45:06.800
Everybody gets this.

00:45:06.800 --> 00:45:09.970
And even some points later
on, you'll get to the point

00:45:09.970 --> 00:45:12.010
where you feel like,
what am I doing here?

00:45:12.010 --> 00:45:14.710
And pointing out that there
is a lot of imposter syndrome

00:45:14.710 --> 00:45:17.140
at Google, and
pointing out that it's

00:45:17.140 --> 00:45:19.390
normal-- which is very
helpful, especially when you're

00:45:19.390 --> 00:45:19.955
starting out.

00:45:19.955 --> 00:45:21.580
DANIEL JACKSON: Yeah,
that's very good.

00:45:21.580 --> 00:45:23.440
I think just setting
expectations.

00:45:23.440 --> 00:45:25.150
I think that's one
of the things that's

00:45:25.150 --> 00:45:27.500
very demoralizing for
people who somehow--

00:45:27.500 --> 00:45:30.190
particularly if they came from
an experience early in life

00:45:30.190 --> 00:45:33.307
when everything was easy, and
then suddenly it's not easy.

00:45:33.307 --> 00:45:35.140
And maybe if they could
just be told-- maybe

00:45:35.140 --> 00:45:36.585
we need to do a
better job of that

00:45:36.585 --> 00:45:38.710
as well-- telling people
it's not going to be easy,

00:45:38.710 --> 00:45:40.649
and here are the
challenges you'll face.

00:45:40.649 --> 00:45:42.190
AUDIENCE: I know
you said you weren't

00:45:42.190 --> 00:45:44.290
part of the overall
program that deals

00:45:44.290 --> 00:45:48.100
with the application of
this, but have you changed

00:45:48.100 --> 00:45:49.960
the way you teach
within your classroom

00:45:49.960 --> 00:45:52.114
at all, incorporating
any of these ideas?

00:45:52.114 --> 00:45:53.780
DANIEL JACKSON: That's
a great question.

00:45:53.780 --> 00:45:55.519
Have I changed in
my own classroom?

00:45:55.519 --> 00:45:58.060
So I have to first admit that
that makes me feel tremendously

00:45:58.060 --> 00:46:00.340
guilty, because one of the
things that we did was we

00:46:00.340 --> 00:46:01.540
tracked the amount
of time people

00:46:01.540 --> 00:46:03.581
spent on the programming
assignments in my course

00:46:03.581 --> 00:46:06.880
this term, and I don't dare to
tell you what the numbers were.

00:46:06.880 --> 00:46:12.507
But suffice it to say it was
a classic MIT Firehose course.

00:46:12.507 --> 00:46:14.590
Who would have thought
that learning Node.js could

00:46:14.590 --> 00:46:17.511
take so long and then you'd
need more than three days to do

00:46:17.511 --> 00:46:18.010
that?

00:46:18.010 --> 00:46:19.530
I mean, who would imagine?

00:46:19.530 --> 00:46:23.150
And it turns out you need
more than three days.

00:46:23.150 --> 00:46:24.970
And so I think I've
done, actually,

00:46:24.970 --> 00:46:27.130
pretty badly in my
own course-- certainly

00:46:27.130 --> 00:46:30.580
in terms of cranking down the
pressure, and that's something

00:46:30.580 --> 00:46:33.640
I know we really
need to work on.

00:46:33.640 --> 00:46:37.030
I think I've become better--

00:46:37.030 --> 00:46:38.680
I hope in a couple of respects.

00:46:38.680 --> 00:46:43.050
One is that when a student
wants to come and talk to me,

00:46:43.050 --> 00:46:45.190
I never, ever, any
longer say, well,

00:46:45.190 --> 00:46:46.717
have you checked with the TA?

00:46:46.717 --> 00:46:48.300
Because I'm worried
that they're going

00:46:48.300 --> 00:46:50.850
to ask me something about
installing Node or something

00:46:50.850 --> 00:46:53.280
that is really a
technical question

00:46:53.280 --> 00:46:55.109
that the TA can do
better than me anyway.

00:46:55.109 --> 00:46:57.150
And I've come to realize
that when a student goes

00:46:57.150 --> 00:46:59.670
to a professor, they
have a reason they

00:46:59.670 --> 00:47:01.980
want to talk to you,
and that often is not

00:47:01.980 --> 00:47:03.930
what the pretext is.

00:47:03.930 --> 00:47:06.930
I think I've also
learned that when

00:47:06.930 --> 00:47:08.790
people come to talk to you--

00:47:08.790 --> 00:47:13.260
I had a very MIT-ish attitude,
engineering attitude,

00:47:13.260 --> 00:47:15.300
that you have to solve
people's problems.

00:47:15.300 --> 00:47:17.490
So someone's feeling sad
or depressed or whatever,

00:47:17.490 --> 00:47:18.520
you have to know what to do.

00:47:18.520 --> 00:47:20.160
You have to say, well,
here's what you do.

00:47:20.160 --> 00:47:20.880
Get more exercise.

00:47:20.880 --> 00:47:21.330
Get more sleep.

00:47:21.330 --> 00:47:22.246
Go see a psychiatrist.

00:47:22.246 --> 00:47:23.460
Go see a psychologist.

00:47:23.460 --> 00:47:26.020
Go to MIT Mental Health.

00:47:26.020 --> 00:47:29.280
And I came to realize how
incredibly misguided this is.

00:47:29.280 --> 00:47:31.650
First of all, you can't
solve their problems.

00:47:31.650 --> 00:47:34.139
But secondly, they don't want
you to solve their problems.

00:47:34.139 --> 00:47:35.430
They're smarter than you think.

00:47:35.430 --> 00:47:36.900
If they wanted you to
solve their problems,

00:47:36.900 --> 00:47:38.640
they wouldn't be coming to a
computer science professor.

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:40.530
They could be going
to a psychologist.

00:47:40.530 --> 00:47:41.490
The reason they
come in to you is

00:47:41.490 --> 00:47:43.590
because they want you to
listen to their problems.

00:47:43.590 --> 00:47:45.690
And so I've realized
that actually, it's

00:47:45.690 --> 00:47:47.910
a lot easier than
you might imagine.

00:47:47.910 --> 00:47:49.980
And I think, as
faculty, we just need

00:47:49.980 --> 00:47:51.990
to realize that sometimes
our students just

00:47:51.990 --> 00:47:55.210
need us to listen to them
and to pay attention.

00:47:55.210 --> 00:47:58.270
So I hope I've improved
in that respect.

00:47:58.270 --> 00:48:03.360
But in the structural respects
of the class, I have to admit--

00:48:03.360 --> 00:48:05.700
that needs some work.

00:48:05.700 --> 00:48:08.640
And it's also particularly
challenging in a large class.

00:48:08.640 --> 00:48:13.272
I think in a small
class it's a bit easier,

00:48:13.272 --> 00:48:14.730
because you can
build relationships

00:48:14.730 --> 00:48:15.624
with the students.

00:48:15.624 --> 00:48:17.040
I should say one
exciting thing is

00:48:17.040 --> 00:48:19.577
that some of the counselors
from MIT Mental Health

00:48:19.577 --> 00:48:21.660
have been doing a freshman
seminar this fall using

00:48:21.660 --> 00:48:24.990
my book on resilience, so
I'm very interested to see

00:48:24.990 --> 00:48:26.581
how that will turn out.

00:48:26.581 --> 00:48:28.080
AUDIENCE: I just
wanted to comment--

00:48:28.080 --> 00:48:29.955
because I brought this
up in a Google context

00:48:29.955 --> 00:48:33.510
before-- that I think the
partner skills or resilience

00:48:33.510 --> 00:48:35.430
are compassion and humility.

00:48:35.430 --> 00:48:37.140
And for people
who don't struggle

00:48:37.140 --> 00:48:39.450
with any kind of mental
illness or barriers,

00:48:39.450 --> 00:48:42.210
if we can teach them to be more
compassionate and more humble,

00:48:42.210 --> 00:48:44.177
it supports the
work of the people

00:48:44.177 --> 00:48:46.260
who need to be resilient
because of various things

00:48:46.260 --> 00:48:47.176
they'll struggle with.

00:48:47.176 --> 00:48:49.440
So just something
to think about.

00:48:49.440 --> 00:48:51.480
I taught freshman CS
for a couple years,

00:48:51.480 --> 00:48:53.310
and I specifically
worked with my students

00:48:53.310 --> 00:48:55.140
on compassion, humility,
and resilience.

00:48:55.140 --> 00:48:57.000
And so I think we
would all do well

00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:59.780
to consider those three values
in our workplaces and courses.

00:48:59.780 --> 00:49:02.280
DANIEL JACKSON: I think that
that's a great point, actually.

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:04.620
And one thing to mention
is that at MIT, there's

00:49:04.620 --> 00:49:06.917
been an explosion of
these failure activities.

00:49:06.917 --> 00:49:09.000
There was an undergraduate
one and a graduate one,

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:12.300
both of which I was
honored to participate in.

00:49:12.300 --> 00:49:14.669
I guess I was honored
to be chosen as someone

00:49:14.669 --> 00:49:16.710
whose failures were
considered major enough to be

00:49:16.710 --> 00:49:18.411
able to talk about them.

00:49:18.411 --> 00:49:20.160
But I think that's
actually a great move--

00:49:20.160 --> 00:49:23.055
having people talk very publicly
about failure and about how

00:49:23.055 --> 00:49:24.180
they've coped with failure.

00:49:24.180 --> 00:49:27.390
And I also think it's actually
interesting pedagogically,

00:49:27.390 --> 00:49:30.540
because I think that people
who are good at something

00:49:30.540 --> 00:49:32.236
are normally-- it's
not that they just

00:49:32.236 --> 00:49:34.110
have a natural ability
and they get it right.

00:49:34.110 --> 00:49:35.526
It's that they've
actually learned

00:49:35.526 --> 00:49:37.382
how to deal with things
when they go wrong.

00:49:37.382 --> 00:49:39.090
I mean, that's what
crafts are all about.

00:49:39.090 --> 00:49:41.910
It's not that you can measure
perfectly and cut perfectly.

00:49:41.910 --> 00:49:43.950
It's that you know
how to adjust things

00:49:43.950 --> 00:49:46.780
when things are slightly off.

00:49:46.780 --> 00:49:48.542
And I'm reminded
of how I finally--

00:49:48.542 --> 00:49:50.250
I had been working
with my daughter, when

00:49:50.250 --> 00:49:51.960
she was a teenager,
for many years trying

00:49:51.960 --> 00:49:54.150
to help her get into math.

00:49:54.150 --> 00:49:57.820
And she was so fearful of it and
so convinced she was bad at it.

00:49:57.820 --> 00:50:00.900
And finally, I got her to
admit that she actually

00:50:00.900 --> 00:50:03.660
thought that if she
was good at math, then

00:50:03.660 --> 00:50:05.790
the answers would come
back to her immediately.

00:50:05.790 --> 00:50:07.544
She wouldn't need to think hard.

00:50:07.544 --> 00:50:09.960
And what I explained to her
was that might be true for one

00:50:09.960 --> 00:50:12.360
in a million, really,
really extraordinary,

00:50:12.360 --> 00:50:14.747
off-the-charts math
students, but actually,

00:50:14.747 --> 00:50:16.830
most of the students who
are really good at math--

00:50:16.830 --> 00:50:19.080
they're good at it because
they're good at the thinking,

00:50:19.080 --> 00:50:21.070
and they're not frightened
to do the thinking.

00:50:21.070 --> 00:50:23.310
And that what she needed to
do was get over that fear

00:50:23.310 --> 00:50:26.090
and realize that
it isn't natural.

00:50:26.090 --> 00:50:27.420
It doesn't come naturally.

00:50:27.420 --> 00:50:30.000
And that if you can
sit with the problem,

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:31.660
then you can actually
make progress.

00:50:31.660 --> 00:50:33.410
And I think that made
some change for her.

00:50:33.410 --> 00:50:36.150
So I think that this idea of
us all being a bit more humble

00:50:36.150 --> 00:50:38.040
and explaining that
things are hard--

00:50:38.040 --> 00:50:40.590
I think can also be
pedagogically very powerful

00:50:40.590 --> 00:50:42.460
as well.

00:50:42.460 --> 00:50:43.390
Thank you all so much.

00:50:43.390 --> 00:50:44.730
It's been a pleasure being here.

00:50:44.730 --> 00:50:48.080
[APPLAUSE]

